1 Introduction

This report presents a comprehensive analysis of Bellabeat fitness tracker data, following the structured data analysis process:

  • Ask Phase: Define the business objectives and questions
  • Prepare Phase: Import and explore the fitness datasets
  • Process Phase: Clean and transform the datasets
  • Analyze Phase: Generate descriptive statistics and insights
  • Share Phase: Visualize and communicate key findings

2 Ask Phase

2.0.1 Business Task:

Analyze user engagement patterns, health behaviors, and fitness trends from smart device usage data to inform Bellabeats marketing strategy.

2.0.2 Business Objective:

This project analyzes fitness tracker data from March to May (2016) to understand how users interact with Bellabeat products, identify engagement patterns, and uncover health behavior trends. The findings will guide marketing strategies to improve user retention and product adoption.

4 Process Phase

4.1 Cleaning the Datasets

To prepare the fitness data for analysis, I applied the following steps across all datasets:

  • Cleaned column names for consistency using janitor::clean_names()
  • Converted date columns to proper DateTime format using lubridate
  • Removed duplicates and irrelevant columns
  • Handled missing values and unrealistic data points
  • Performed data integrity checks for consistency
  • Created new features for engagement analysis
  • Merged time-period datasets for comprehensive analysis

4.2 March to April Daily Activity Dataset Cleaning

daily_activity_1 <- daily_activity_1 %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(activity_date = mdy(activity_date)) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  select(-logged_activities_distance, -sedentary_active_distance)

# Data quality check
daily_activity_1 %>%
  mutate(check_distance = very_active_distance + 
           moderately_active_distance + 
           light_active_distance) %>%
  summarise(match_rate = mean(abs(check_distance - total_distance) < 0.01))
## # A tibble: 1  1
##   match_rate
##        <dbl>

colSums(is.na(daily_activity_1))

daily_activity_1 %>%
  summarise(max_steps = max(total_steps),
            min_steps = min(total_steps),
            max_calories = max(calories),
            min_calories = min(calories))
## # A tibble: 1  4
##   max_steps min_steps max_calories min_calories
##       <dbl>     <dbl>        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1     28497         0         4562            0
# Remove unrealistic values
daily_activity_1 <- daily_activity_1 %>%
  filter(total_steps > 0 & calories > 0)

# Feature engineering
daily_activity_1 <- daily_activity_1 %>%
  mutate(
    weekday = weekdays(activity_date),
    active_minutes_total = very_active_minutes + fairly_active_minutes + lightly_active_minutes,
    engagement_level = case_when(
      total_steps < 5000 ~ "Low",
      total_steps < 10000 ~ "Moderate",
      TRUE ~ "High"
    )
  )

# Save cleaned dataset
write_csv(daily_activity_1, 
          "F:/Google_Data_Analysis/case_studies/case_study_2/case_study_2_datasets/cleaned_datasets/daily_activity_clean_first.csv")

weight_log_1 <- weight_log_1 %>%
  clean_names() %>%

  distinct()

# Check missing values
colSums(is.na(weight_log_1))

  summarise(max_weight = max(weight_kg, na.rm = TRUE),

4.11 Sleep Day Dataset Cleaning

sleep_day <- sleep_day %>%
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(sleep_day = mdy_hms(sleep_day)) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  filter(
    total_minutes_asleep >= 120 & total_minutes_asleep <= 960,
    total_time_in_bed >= 120 & total_time_in_bed <= 1100,
    total_minutes_asleep <= total_time_in_bed
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    sleep_efficiency = round((total_minutes_asleep / total_time_in_bed) * 100, 1),
    awake_minutes = total_time_in_bed - total_minutes_asleep,
    weekday = weekdays(sleep_day)
  )

# Save cleaned dataset
write_csv(sleep_day,
          "F:/Google_Data_Analysis/case_studies/case_study_2/case_study_2_datasets/cleaned_datasets/sleep_day_clean.csv")

5.6 Cross-Dataset Insights (Marketing Value)

safe_cor <- function(x, y) {
  if (sum(complete.cases(x, y)) > 1) {
    return(cor(x, y, use = "complete.obs"))
  } else {
    return(NA)
  }
}

activity_sleep <- daily_activity %>%
  left_join(sleep_day, by = c("id" = "id", "activity_date" = "sleep_day"))

cor_steps_sleep <- safe_cor(activity_sleep$total_steps, activity_sleep$total_minutes_asleep)

activity_weight <- daily_activity %>%
  left_join(weight_log, by = c("id" = "id", "activity_date" = "date"))

cor_calories_bmi <- safe_cor(activity_weight$calories, activity_weight$bmi)

activity_hr <- daily_activity %>%
  left_join(heart_rate_daily, by = c("id" = "id", "activity_date" = "date"))

cor_activity_hr <- safe_cor(activity_hr$total_steps, activity_hr$avg_hr)

6.1 Custom Visualization Theme

custom_theme <- theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5), 
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, hjust = 0.5, margin = margin(b = 10)), 
    axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13, margin = margin(t = 10)),
    axis.title.y = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13, margin = margin(r = 10)),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 11),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey85"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

# Helper function to order weekdays
order_weekdays <- function(df, colname) {
  weekday_levels <- c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")
  df %>%
    mutate("{colname}" := factor(.data[[colname]], levels = weekday_levels))
}

7 Conclusion

The analysis revealed several key insights about Bellabeat users:

  • Activity Patterns: Users show strong correlation between steps and calories burned, with most users falling into moderate to high engagement levels
  • Weekly Trends: Sedentary behavior peaks on Mondays and Fridays, suggesting work-related patterns
  • Sleep Habits: Users get less sleep on weekdays compared to weekends, with average sleep efficiency around 8590%
  • Health Metrics: Most users maintain healthy BMI ranges (average ~25) and heart rates
  • Cross-Correlations: Positive relationships exist between activity levels, sleep quality, and overall health metrics

7.1 Key Findings

  • 65% of users maintain moderate to high engagement levels
  • Average daily steps: 8,200 steps
  • Average sleep duration: 7.1 hours per night
  • Strong correlation: r = 0.59 between steps and calories burned
  • 72% of weight logs are manually reported, indicating engaged users

8 Recommendations

  • Targeted Engagement Programs: Develop programs for low-engagement users to increase daily activity levels
  • Weekday Activity Challenges: Create incentives for increased activity during sedentary weekdays (Mondays and Fridays)
  • Sleep Optimization Features: Enhance sleep tracking with personalized recommendations for better sleep efficiency
  • Integration Opportunities: Leverage the strong correlation between activity and sleep to create integrated wellness programs
  • Manual Reporting Incentives: Reward users who manually log data to encourage consistent engagement

By implementing these strategies, Bellabeat can increase user engagement, improve retention rates, and enhance overall user satisfaction with their fitness products.
